bio: • My name is Joshua Bryant and I’m from Huron County, Michigan. I’m a professional engineer and a software developer, I work for a manufacturing company’s R&D department. I also run a few side ventures involving web design, application dev, & microcontroller programming. I have proficient skills in 3D modeling and assemblies to which I use in my newest venture ‘3D Printing’. I print using an “Orion Delta” from SeeMeCNC.

My experience with 3D printers started with a MakerBot Replicator 2X, and expanded some years later to an Ultimaker 3, after which I soon purchased my own Prusa i3 MK2S kit and, another year later, I upgraded to my latest Prusa i3 MK3 kit. I've been designing/engineering for nearly a decade and a half, primarily with SolidWorks. Mostly (at home) I print for fun, with the occasional, useful item to be sure to justify the expense. My oldest child is a creative type and just got started with a 3D pen, the Scribbler DUO. At work, many a prototype has been extruded out, so much so that we've worn out the Ultimaker 3. But no tears as a Prusa i3 MK3 now graces my desk at work too! (Thankfully it is MUCH quieter than the MakerBot and Ultimaker models)
PLA is my preferred filament, since it prints so well, but I really like TPU as well. I'm excited to try out my new spool of food grade PETG as well. I hardly touch my ABS filaments, and I'm hoping to replace the need to use ABS for the higher temperature applications with PETG. We'll see!

I love the Wanhoa printer, but am a bit tired of calibrating it constantly. Also I am hoping for the next 3d print technology to become more affordable.
I'm 27 at the time of this account creation and I am just stepping into the world of 3d printing!
I am a doctor, a friend of u.
Retired engineer now developing electronics for leisure marine sailing industry.

I'm Big into modeling Larger scales and am an Illustrator old school. I have been wanting to learn this technology since I first seen it. I also am a "Munster's Fan" I am currently doing both the Munster Cars in 8th scale and hoping to be able to use 3-D printed parts in the future.

Living the exciting life of a crazy artist that nobody understands. I love programming, illustration, industrial design, oil painting, playing electric guitar/bass/keyboard, and music production. If I am not working at the hackerspace, I take breaks to hike and explore abandoned industrial buildings.
